utex IPC |\n| open+close | 30.8 | 3.4 | 9.1x | Shadow FD creation (memfd + LKL pread loop) |\n| lseek+read | 1.4 | 1.0 | 1.4x | Near native (CONTINUE path) |\n| write | 1.2 | 1.1 | 1.1x | Near native (CONTINUE path) |\n\n## Future Work: Acceleration Roadmap\n\nStrategies ranked by impact/complexity ratio.  Estimated reductions are per\nLKL-touching syscall.\n\n### Tier A: High impact, low complexity\n\n**1. Stop shadow promotion on fstat** (est. -10 to -50us on first fstat)\n\n`forward_fstat` currently calls `ensure_same_fd_shadow` which triggers full\n`memfd_create` + LKL pread loop just to answer metadata.  Shadow creation\nshould only happen on `mmap`, not `fstat`.  Most `open+fstat+close` sequences\n(config files, directory listings) never mmap.\n\n**2. FD-local stat cache** (est. -2 to -6us per stat hit)\n\nStore `struct stat` in `kbox_fd_entry` on first `open`/`fstat`.  Subsequent\n`fstat(fd)` returns cached metadata without LKL round-trip.  Invalidate on\nwrite/truncate/rename to the same FD.  Extends `struct kbox_fd_entry` with\na cached stat + validity generation.\n\n**3. Cacheline separation in IPC struct** (est. -0.3 to -1us)\n\nSplit `has_pending_request` and `has_pending_dispatch` onto separate 64-byte\ncache lines in `kbox_syscall_trap_runtime`.  Eliminates false sharing between\nguest and service threads on x86_64.\n\n### Tier B: High impact, medium complexity\n\n**4. Inode-keyed shadow FD cache** (est. -20 to -200us on repeated opens)\n\nCache memfds by `(dev, inode, mtime, size)`.  Repeated opens of the same\nDSO/executable reuse existing memfd via `/proc/self/fd/` reopen.  Invalidate\non write/truncate/rename/unlink.  Already scoped in TODO.md.  This is the\nsingle biggest win for open+close latency.\n\n**5. Adaptive SQPOLL** (est. -1 to -5us on syscall bursts)\n\nAfter servicing one LKL syscall, spin for a short window before sleeping.\nCatches `openat → fstat → close` clusters without dedicating a core\nfull-time.  Hybrid between the current 1024